args:
1: A string that references a sprite stored in a character's COL file
2: Duration in game ticks
description:
Display a frame of animation, and it's matching hurtbox/hitbox/EX_POINT, for a certain amount of game ticks.
Function calls underneath sprite will be active for the duration of that sprite call.
extra:
Function calls underneath sprite will be active throughout the duration of that sprite.
You cannot call sprite within an if-block!
Note that hurt/hitboxes are tied to their animation frames, and need to be adjusted seperately from BBScript.

description: Check if a variable is true (read: anything except the value 0).

args:
1: Operator
2: Variable or integer
3: Variable or integer
description: Same as 'if', but applies an operation on the first variable before checking whether it's true or not.
Check if a variable is false (read: the value 0).

Traditionally known as an interrupt.\nTriggers the block of code within when the object/player receives the matching signal.\nSome signals are sent by the game itself (IDLING, ATTACK_COLLISION etc.), some can be triggered manually with various function calls.
extra:
Any code placed in an upon block, will trigger immediately when it's event occurs.
[upon: (TOUCH_GROUND)
  jumpToLabel: s32'landing'
  endUpon:]
Protip: Check the upon tab at the top of this website for all events.
Clears the interrupt, meaning the code within will no longer trigger even if it's event occurs.

description: Exit current state immediately and go to the given state.

args:
1: TIMER or FALL SPEED
2: if TIMER the second arg sets a timer in frame duration on when to go to the TIMER upon
description: Used for triggering delayed interrupts, aka timers.
extra:
Here's an example.
This piece of code disables invulnerability after 10 game ticks.
[setEventTrigger: (TIMER), 10
upon: (TIMER)
  enableSuperArmor: 0
  endUpon:]

description: Execute code on a different object.

args:
1: The STACK to put the object into
2: The actual object (usually PREVIOUS)
description: Store a reference to a specific object in any of the generic STACK objects
extra:
First we create a ki-blast, then store it in STACK7.
[createObject: s32'kidan_5D', 0
putObjectIntoStack: (STACK7), (PREVIOUS)]
We can manipulate it later, to for example flip it's direction.
[applyTo: (STACK7)
  flipDirection:
  endApply:]
